## What I Learned:

**Active vs Passive Reconnaissance**
- Active reconnaissance involves directly interacting with the target system, which can leave traces in logs (IP addresses, timestamps)
- Unlike passive methods that rely on publicly available information, active techniques provide more detailed and specific data but are more intrusive
- Requires proper authorization before conducting any active probing

**Web Browser as Recon Tool**
- Web browsers connect to targets on common ports (TCP 80 for HTTP, TCP 443 for HTTPS)
- Developer Tools (Ctrl+Shift+I on PC, Option+Command+I on Mac) allow inspection of JavaScript files, cookies, and site structure
- Browser extensions like Wappalyzer identify technologies used on websites

**Ping (ICMP)**
- Ping uses ICMP protocol to test reachability of remote systems
- ICMP header size is 8 bytes
- `-s` option sets the size of data carried by the ICMP echo request
- Microsoft Windows Firewall blocks ping by default
- Command: `ping -c 10 [IP]` sends 10 ICMP echo requests

**Traceroute**
- Tracks the path packets take from your system to the destination host
- Identifies each router (hop) along the route and counts the total number
- Useful for mapping network infrastructure and troubleshooting connectivity
- Traceroute A: Last hop before tryhackme.com was 172.67.69.208
- Traceroute B: Last hop was 104.26.11.229 with 26 routers between systems

**Telnet**
- Telnet protocol (default port 23) allows remote command-line interface access
- Transmits all data in cleartext, making it insecure; SSH is the secure alternative
- Can be used to grab service banners and identify running services
- Connect to port 80 and issue `GET / HTTP/1.1` to reveal web server details

**Netcat (nc)**
- Versatile tool supporting both TCP and UDP protocols
- Can function as either client or server
- Used for port scanning, banner grabbing, and setting up basic connections
- Connect to FTP port 21 to identify server version

**Key Takeaways**
- Active reconnaissance is essential for gathering detailed intelligence but must be conducted with authorization and stealth in mind
- Even simple tools like web browsers can be powerful reconnaissance assets when used with developer tools and extensions
- Understanding the OSI model and network fundamentals (TCP/IP, ports, protocols) is crucial for effective reconnaissance

